[[File:Subretinal stimulation.png|thumb|Photovoltaic array implanted under the degenerate retina converts NIR light into electric current flowing through the tissue and stimulating the inner retinal neurons.]]

'''Photovoltaic retinal prosthesis''' is a technology for restoring sight to patients blinded by [[Degeneration (medical)|degenerative]] [[retina]]l diseases, such as [[retinitis pigmentosa]] and [[Macular degeneration|age-related macular degeneration]] (AMD), when patients lose the 'image capturing' photoreceptors, but [[neuron]]s in the 'image-processing' inner retinal layers are relatively well-preserved <ref name="Photovoltaic retinal prosthesis: implant fabrication and performance.">{{cite journal |doi=10.1088/1741-2560/9/4/046014 |title=Photovoltaic retinal prosthesis: Implant fabrication and performance |year=2012 |last1=Wang |first1=Lele |journal=Journal of Neural Engineering |volume=9 |issue=4 |pages=046014 |pmc=3419261 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>. This subretinal [[prosthesis]] is designed to restore a patients' sight by electrically stimulating the surviving inner retinal neurons, primarily the bipolar cells. Photovoltaic retinal implants are completely wireless and powered by near-infrared illumination (880nm) projected from the video goggles. Therefore, they do not require such complex surgical methods as needed for other retinal implants, which are powered via extraocular electronics connected to the retinal array by a trans-scleral cable <ref name="Photovoltaic retinal prosthesis with high pixel density">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nphoton.2012.104 |title=Photovoltaic retinal prosthesis with high pixel density |year=2012 |last1=Mathieson |first1=Keith |journal=Nature Photonics |volume=6 |pages=391–397 |pmc=3462820 |display-authors=etal }}</ref>. Optical activation of the photovoltaic pixels allows scaling the implants to thousands of electrodes. [[File:Photovoltaic array with 40um pixels.png|thumb|left|180 px|Photovoltaic array with 40μm pixels imaged on top of the retinal pigment epithelium.]]
{{Orphan|date=November 2012}}
Studies in rats with retinal degeneration demonstrated that prosthetic vision with such subretinal implants preserves many features of natural vision, including flicker fusion at high frequencies (>20 Hz), adaptation to static images, center-surround organization and non-linear summation of subunits in receptive fields, providing high spatial resolution<ref>{{cite journal |title=Spatio-temporal Characteristics of Retinal Response to Network-mediated Photovoltaic Stimulation |author=E. Ho |journal=Journal of Neurophysiology |volume=119 |pages=389–400 |year=2018 |display-authors=etal }}</ref>. Grating visual acuity measured with 70μm pixels matches the sampling density limit (pixel pitch)<ref>{{cite journal |title=Photovoltaic Restoration of Sight with High Visual Acuity |author=H. Lorach |journal=Nature Medicine |volume=21 |pages=476–482 |year=2015 |display-authors=etal }}</ref>. Clinical trial with these implants ([http://www.pixium-vision.com/en/technology-1/prima-vision-restoration-system PRIMA], Pixium Vision) having 100μm pixels started in 2018, and the initial results already confirmed that patients indeed perceive projected patterns with spatial resolution limited by the pixel size. Implants with pixels of 50μm and smaller are being developed by [http://web.stanford.edu/~palanker/lab/retinalpros.html Palanker group] at [https://www.stanford.edu/ Stanford University]. 
